 central bowl.\",\n        \"Defend the rite from intruders attracted by the lightwell.\",\n        \"Hold a perimeter in silence while moth-keepers seal the opening.\",\n        \"Capture one echo in a mothwax jar without letting it speak your true name.\",\n        \"Return with Pesha to the House of Quiet Wings and report to the Archive.\"\n      ],\n      \"dialogue\": [\n        {\"speaker\": \"Pesha Lume\", \"lines\": \"The Scar remembers what we forget, and it forgets what we cling to, like a ledger that erases grief and keeps debt. If an echo offers you comfort, it is reaching for your spine, and comfort is the oldest knife in the dark. We will speak only in agreed signs once we cross the bowl, because the Scar loves the shapes of names and will bend toward them as reeds bend to wind. You will not answer to your name if it is sung, whistled, abraded in the glass, or braided in a friend’s mouth, because the thing that speaks it may never have had a mouth at all. You have already traded one syllable to this place, and the Scar keeps bargains, so I will not let it tax you twice even if I must spend my own breath to cover yours.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Kade Orrel\", \"lines\": \"The first time I stood in that bowl the world felt like a bell that had just been struck, and the strike rang in my bones long after my ears went dull. My breath came back wrong and my fear felt like someone else’s memory, as if I had borrowed panic and returned it chipped. I can carry a shield and keep my mouth shut, and my rope knows the Scar’s edges better than most skiffs know their own cleats. But if something wears my voice, I want you to promise you’ll break the jar rather than let it walk home with us, because I would rather lose a weapon than come back with a thief in my lungs. I have hauled friends from the thief’s gate and cut knots that should never have been tied, and I will do both again before I let a bad light learn my name.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Kara Dusk\", 