ers will come with curiosity, with greed, or with the courage of fools, and each demands a different silence, so measure your quiet like a surgeon measures thread. If an echo slides along your blade and reaches for your ear, tilt your head to the wind and let the Wardens’ line sing through you, because their hum can scatter the smallest of the hungry things. When we are done, I will press the warm seal with my thumb, and you will smell honey where there is none, and you will know that the mouth of the night has closed for now.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Pesha Lume\", \"lines\": \"When the lightwell closes, there will be a moment when all sounds seem further away, like children stepping back from a game because the rules changed. Do not mistake that for safety, because the dark rearranges itself like a sleeper rolling over, and sleepers sometimes reach blindly for warmth and find a throat. We will leave a moth to watch our backs; it will die for us if asked, and we will add its name to the wax, because our order keeps accounts even when our eyes do not. If you must choose between a stranger’s lantern and the jar in your hand, choose the jar, because we can relight a lantern but we cannot unsay a name once the Scar has pocketed it. Walk beside me until speech becomes a weight we cannot afford, and then shoulder that weight with your silence and let me spend the rest.\"}\n      ],\n      \"choices\": [\n        {\"id\": \"C1\", \"title\": \"Walk the Scar in Severed Silence\", \"text\": \"You vow to use only hand-signs and drum-taps on the rope, and you bind your wrist with a strip of mothcloth that tickles when your throat tries to rise. You brief Mira and Lysa on perimeter signals, scratch a map into the sand with your boarding hook, and mark four glass ribs with chalk to show fallback points if the night bucks. You signal Kara Dusk overhead with a low sweep that reads hold your height, and she answers with a kite tilt that means I see you but you do not see me. Whe